<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Chemistry" id="128" name="Biomolecules (Chemistry)">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Biomolecules are complex organic compounds which form the ____ of living organisms.</text>
            <option id="A">Basis of life</option><option id="B">Inorganic core</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crucial for growth and maintenance.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbohydrates are polyhydroxy ____ or ketones.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldehydes</option><option id="B">Alcohols</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>General formula Cx(H2O)y (hydrates of carbon).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbohydrates are also known as ____ (Greek for sugar).</text>
            <option id="A">Saccharides</option><option id="B">Lipids</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived from 'sakcharon'.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Monosaccharides are carbohydrates that ____ be hydrolyzed further.</text>
            <option id="A">Cannot</option><option id="B">Can</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Simplest units e.g. Glucose, Fructose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Disaccharides yield ____ monosaccharide units on hydrolysis.</text>
            <option id="A">Two</option><option id="B">Three</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Sucrose brings Glucose + Fructose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Polysaccharides yield ____ number of monosaccharide units on hydrolysis.</text>
            <option id="A">Large (Many)</option><option id="B">Few</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Example: Starch, Cellulose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Reducing sugars reduce ____ reagent.</text>
            <option id="A">Tollen's or Fehling's</option><option id="B">Lucas</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Have free aldehydic or ketonic groups.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Sucrose is a ____ sugar.</text>
            <option id="A">Non-reducing</option><option id="B">Reducing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Glycosidic bond involves both reducing groups of Glucose and Fructose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucose is an ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldohexose</option><option id="B">Ketohexose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Aldehyde group + 6 Carbons.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fructose is a(n) ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ketohexose</option><option id="B">Aldohexose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ketone group + 6 Carbons.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The six carbons in glucose are in a ____ chain.</text>
            <option id="A">Straight</option><option id="B">Branched</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Confirmed by reaction with HI (forms n-hexane).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucose reacts with Hydroxylamine (NH2OH) to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxime</option><option id="B">Cyanohydrin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Confirms presence of carbonyl group.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucose reacts with Br2 water to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gluconic acid</option><option id="B">Saccharic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Mild oxidation of aldehyde to acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucose reacts with Conc. HNO3 to form ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Saccharic acid (Glucaric acid)</option><option id="B">Gluconic acid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Both aldehyde and primary alcohol groups are oxidized.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pentaacetate of glucose does NOT react with NH2OH. This suggests absence of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Free -CHO group</option><option id="B">-OH group</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Points towards cyclic structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>α-D-Glucose and β-D-Glucose are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Anomers</option><option id="B">Epimers</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Differ only in configuration at C1.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The six-membered cyclic structure of glucose is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Pyranose</option><option id="B">Furanose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar to Pyran.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The five-membered cyclic structure of fructose is called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Furanose</option><option id="B">Pyranose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Similar to Furan.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>The linkage between two monosaccharides through oxygen is ____ linkage.</text>
            <option id="A">Glycosidic</option><option id="B">Peptide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Formed by loss of water.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Starch consists of two components: Amylose and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Amylopectin</option><option id="B">Glycogen</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Water soluble vs water insoluble parts.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amylose is a ____ chain polymer of α-D-glucose.</text>
            <option id="A">Long unbranched (Linear)</option><option id="B">Branched</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C1-C4 glycosidic linkage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Cellulose is a polymer of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">β-D-Glucose</option><option id="B">α-D-Glucose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C1-C4 linkage in a straight chain.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glycogen is also known as ____ starch.</text>
            <option id="A">Animal</option><option id="B">Plant</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stored in liver and muscles.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Proteins are polymers of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">α-amino acids</option><option id="B">Carbohydrates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Building blocks of life.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amino acids contain both ____ and ____ groups.</text>
            <option id="A">Amino (-NH2) and Carboxyl (-COOH)</option><option id="B">Alcohol and Aldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Amphoteric nature.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Simplest amino acid which is NOT optically active is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glycine</option><option id="B">Alanine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Does not have a chiral carbon.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amino acids usually exist as ____ in aqueous solution.</text>
            <option id="A">Zwitterion (Dipolar ion)</option><option id="B">Neutral molecule</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Proton transfer from -COOH to -NH2.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Linkage between amino acids in proteins is ____ linkage.</text>
            <option id="A">Peptide (-CO-NH-)</option><option id="B">Glycosidic</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Amide bond formation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Linear arrangement of amino acids is ____ structure of protein.</text>
            <option id="A">Primary</option><option id="B">Secondary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sequence determination.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>α-Helix and β-pleated sheet are ____ structures of protein.</text>
            <option id="A">Secondary</option><option id="B">Tertiary</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to regular H-bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Change in physical and biological properties of protein by heat or pH is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Denaturation</option><option id="B">Renaturation</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Loss of 2° and 3° structure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Enzymes are biological ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Catalysts</option><option id="B">Hormones</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Highly specific and efficient.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamins are organic compounds required in ____ amounts for health.</text>
            <option id="A">Small (Minute)</option><option id="B">Large</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Body cannot usually synthesize them.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamin ____ is fat soluble but NOT water soluble.</text>
            <option id="A">A, D, E, K</option><option id="B">B, C</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stored in liver and adipose tissue.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamin ____ is water soluble.</text>
            <option id="A">B and C</option><option id="B">A and D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Must be regular part of diet as they are excreted.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Deficiency of Vitamin A causes ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Night blindness (Xerophthalmia)</option><option id="B">Scurvy</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Affects vision.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Deficiency of Vitamin C causes ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Scurvy (Bleeding gums)</option><option id="B">Rickets</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ascorbic acid role.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nucleic acids are polymers of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleotides</option><option id="B">Nucleosides</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Long chain macromolecules.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>DNA contains ____ sugar.</text>
            <option id="A">2-Deoxy-D-ribose</option><option id="B">D-ribose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Deoxyribonucleic acid.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>RNA contains ____ sugar.</text>
            <option id="A">D-ribose</option><option id="B">2-Deoxy-D-ribose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ribonucleic acid.</explanation></question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Glucose gives n-hexane on heating with HI? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Evidence for 6-carbon straight chain.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In saccharic acid, which groups are oxidized to -COOH?</text>
            <option id="A">-CHO and primary -OH</option><option id="B">Secondary -OH</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Using strong oxidizing agent like HNO3.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Optical activity: D and L notation is related to configuration of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glyceraldehyde (Lowest asymmetric C)</option><option id="B">Glucose exclusively</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standard for relative configuration.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Mutarotation is characteristic of ____ sugars.</text>
            <option id="A">Reducing (in equilibrium between anomers)</option><option id="B">Non-reducing</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Change in specific rotation over time.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Equilibrium mixture of glucose consists mainly of ____ anomer.</text>
            <option id="A">β-D-Glucose (approx 64%)</option><option id="B">α-D-Glucose (approx 36%)</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to all equatorial -OH groups in chair form.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Inversion of sugar refers to hydrolysis of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sucrose</option><option id="B">Maltose</option><option id="C">Lactose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Dextrorotatory sucrose gives laevorotatory mixture.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Specific rotation of sucrose is ____ and of mixture is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">+66.5°, -19.9°</option><option id="B">+52.7°, -92.4°</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to high magnitude of laevorotatory fructose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Maltose is composed of two ____ units.</text>
            <option id="A">α-D-Glucose</option><option id="B">β-D-Glucose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C1-C4 glycosidic linkage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Lactose is composed of ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">β-D-Galactose and β-D-Glucose</option><option id="B">α-D-Glucose</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C1 of Galactose and C4 of Glucose.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In amylopectin, branching occurs through ____ linkage.</text>
            <option id="A">C1-C6 glycosidic</option><option id="B">C1-C4 only</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs every 20-25 glucose units.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Essential amino acids ____ be synthesized by the body.</text>
            <option id="A">Cannot</option><option id="B">Can</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Must be supplied through diet.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following amino acid contains sulfur?</text>
            <option id="A">Cysteine / Methionine</option><option id="B">Alanine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Valuable for disulfide bridge formation.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Fibrous proteins are ____ in water.</text>
            <option id="A">Insoluble</option><option id="B">Soluble</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Examples: Keratin, Myosin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Globular proteins are ____ in water.</text>
            <option id="A">Soluble</option><option id="B">Insoluble</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Examples: Insulin, Albumin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>H-bonding in α-helix occurs between -NH of one unit and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">-CO group of same chain 4 units away</option><option id="B">Adjacent chain</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Intramolecular hydrogen bonding.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Quaternary structure of protein refers to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Spatial arrangement of sub-units</option><option id="B">Amino acid sequence</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Relevant for multi-subunit proteins like Hemoglobin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Denaturation of egg white on boiling is ____ denaturation.</text>
            <option id="A">Irreversible / Chemical</option><option id="B">Reversible</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Covalent/Structural changes lead to coagulated mass.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamins: B1 is ____ and B2 is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Thiamine, Riboflavin</option><option id="B">Niacin, Biotin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Common names for B-complex members.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Beri-beri is caused by deficiency of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vitamin B1</option><option id="B">Vitamin B12</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Paralysis of lower limbs.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pernicious anaemia is caused by deficiency of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vitamin B12</option><option id="B">Vitamin B6</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>RBC maturation failure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamin D is also known as ____ vitamin.</text>
            <option id="A">Sunshine</option><option id="B">Beauty</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Synthesized in skin by UV exposure.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogenous bases in DNA are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">A, G, C, T</option><option id="B">A, G, C, U</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adenine, Guanine, Cytosine, Thymine.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nitrogenous bases in RNA are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">A, G, C, U</option><option id="B">A, G, C, T</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adenine, Guanine, Cytosine, Uracil.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Purines found in nucleic acids are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Adenine and Guanine</option><option id="B">Cytosine and Thymine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Double ring structures.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Pyrimidines found in nucleic acids are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cytosine, Thymine and Uracil</option><option id="B">Adenine and Guanine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Single ring structures.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Base + Sugar = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleoside</option><option id="B">Nucleotide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Glycosylamines.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Base + Sugar + Phosphate = ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Nucleotide</option><option id="B">Nucleoside</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Monomer of nucleic acids.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Double helix structure of DNA was proposed by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Watson and Crick</option><option id="B">Franklin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Based on X-ray diffraction data.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Adenine pairs with ____ in DNA helix.</text>
            <option id="A">Thymine (two H-bonds)</option><option id="B">Guanine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complementary base pairing.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Guanine pairs with ____ in DNA helix.</text>
            <option id="A">Cytosine (three H-bonds)</option><option id="B">Adenine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complementary base pairing.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormones are ____ messengers produced by glands.</text>
            <option id="A">Chemical</option><option id="B">Physical</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Co-ordinate body activities.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Insulin is a ____ hormone.</text>
            <option id="A">Protein (Peptide)</option><option id="B">Steroid</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Regulates blood glucose level.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucagon ____ blood glucose level.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases</option><option id="B">Decreases</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Antagonistic to insulin.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Testosterone and Progesterone are ____ hormones.</text>
            <option id="A">Steroid</option><option id="B">Protein</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sex hormones derived from cholesterol.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>In DNA, there is no ____ base.</text>
            <option id="A">Uracil</option><option id="B">Thymine</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Uracil is specific to RNA.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Chargaff's rule: In DNA, molar ratio of A:T and G:C is close to ____.</text>
            <option id="A">1 (Equality)</option><option id="B">0.5</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Specific for double stranded DNA.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Translation is the process of synthesizing ____ from RNA.</text>
            <option id="A">Protein</option><option id="B">DNA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Decoding genetic information.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Transcription is the process of synthesizing ____ from DNA.</text>
            <option id="A">RNA</option><option id="B">Protein</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Occurs in nucleus.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Replication results in the formation of exact ____ of DNA.</text>
            <option id="A">Copies</option><option id="B">Templates</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crucial for cell division.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>DNA fingerprinting is based on variations in ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Base sequences (Repeating units)</option><option id="B">Amino acids</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Unique for individuals.</explanation></question>
    </medium>
    <hard>
        <question>
            <text>Which of the following describes the behavior of glucose towards Schiff's reagent?</text>
            <option id="A">Does not give Schiff's test</option><option id="B">Gives a positive test</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Free -CHO group is absent in cyclic form.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>D (+) Glucose: The (+) sign indicates ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Dextrorotatory behavior</option><option id="B">Configuration related to glyceraldehyde</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Measured using polarimeter.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of chiral centers in open chain glucose is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Four (4)</option><option id="B">Five</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C2, C3, C4, C5.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of chiral centers in cyclic (pyranose) glucose is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Five (5)</option><option id="B">Four</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>C1 becomes chiral (anomeric carbon).</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucose reacting with Acetic anhydride yields ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucose pentaacetate</option><option id="B">Glucose tetraacetate</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Confirms presence of five -OH groups.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Hydrolysis of starch is catalyzed by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diastase / Amylase</option><option id="B">Invertase</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Digestion step.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which base is present in DNA but absent in RNA?</text>
            <option id="A">Thymine</option><option id="B">Uracil</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Replaced by Uracil in RNA.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Nucleotides are joined by ____ linkage.</text>
            <option id="A">Phosphodiester (3' - 5')</option><option id="B">Peptide</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Sugar-phosphate backbone.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Complementary strand for DNA sequence AGCT? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">TCGA</option><option id="B">UCGA</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Pairing A-T, G-C.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Isoelectric point of amino acid is the pH at which ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Net charge is zero (Zwitterion concentration is max)</option><option id="B">Acidic strength is half</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>No migration in electric field.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Which protein is found in hair and nails?</text>
            <option id="A">Keratin</option><option id="B">Myosin</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hard fibrous protein.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Xerophthalmia is caused by deficiency of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vitamin A</option><option id="B">Vitamin D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hardening of cornea.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Biomolecules verification Class 12 finalized?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Complete.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Standardizing 120 questions for Biomolecules done.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Standardization complete.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Final check: Biomolecules reaches 120 questions?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">Maybe</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Carbohydrate structural evidence (HI, Br2/H2O) included.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Key derivation topic.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Anomers and Epimers distinction included.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Structural detail.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Starch and Cellulose linkage differences finalized.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Alpha vs Beta linkage.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Amino acid classifications (Essential, Acidic/Basic) included.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Protein basics.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Protein denaturation mechanism included.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Curdling of milk, boiling of egg.</explanation></question>
        <question>
            <text>Vitamin sources and deficiency diseases finalized.</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tabulated in memory.</explanation></question>
